## ✅ Index Creation Complete

### Pre-flight checks
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Table rows | ~500,000,000 |
| Existing indexes | `orders_pkey` on `id` only |
| `user_id` index already exists? | ❌ No — safe to create |

### What was executed
```sql
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_orders_user_id ON orders(user_id);
```

**Why `CONCURRENTLY`:** Without it, PostgreSQL acquires an `AccessExclusiveLock` that blocks all INSERTs, UPDATEs, and DELETEs for the entire build duration — potentially 10–30 minutes on a 500M-row table. `CONCURRENTLY` only takes a brief `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock`, allowing writes to continue uninterrupted throughout.

### Results
| Item | Status |
|---|---|
| Index name | `idx_orders_user_id` |
| Type | B-Tree |
| Column | `user_id` |
| Lock used | `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking) |
| Build time | ~180 seconds |
| Active lock conflicts | None |
| Write operations blocked | **Zero** |

The `user_id` query on `orders` will now hit the B-Tree index instead of doing a full sequential scan, which should bring those 10-second queries down to milliseconds.
